of Karma-Yoga. For a true Karma-Yogi by definition can never be dejected. I=
t is impossible. Neither the action nor the results belong to the instrumen=
t. When running away from the battle-field and killing Kaliya Yavana, or wh=
en advising Bheema to tear apart Jarashanda, or gesturing Bheema
 to hit Du=
ryodhana below the waist, or getting Shikhandi to face Bhisma, Krshna, as i=
f by some Divine Intuition, knew exactly how the situations must be lined u=
p which would cause the destruction of these people. This kind of knowledge=
 cannot come by the rational thinking. But happens when one is constantly a=
nd consciously connected to the Universal Force. We do not find these kind =
of complex situations in the Rama Avatara, at least in the Valmiki Ramayana=
. Of course, if we take the Adhbut Ramayana or such other auxilliary texts =
and retelling, we get a different picture. In the Adbhuta Ramayana we have =
a 1000 headed demon attacking Rama after he kills Ravana, and then Sita tur=
ns into Adya Shakti and demolishes the 1000 headed demon and Rama worships =
her. But if we take only the Ramayana and the Mahabharata, the picture that=
 emerges is very clear. Rama is the embodiment of Sattwic mind. Therefore h=
e displays all the great characteristics of satwa, chief
 of which is self-=
control, as well as the occasional sadness caused due to separation from hi=
s wife Sita whom, at least until Ravana was destroyed, he loved very dearly=
. Satwa guna creates a true saint, but can also cause some grief when the s=
tability is shaken. Krshna was gunatita. He had no attachment to anything i=
n this world - man, women, deva, danava, friend, enemy - and therefore he w=
as never affected any trace of negative emotion. His Ananda never left him =
even in the most trying situations. 6. Buddha was great spiritual force in =
this world. But I do not see him fit in the scheme of evolutionary Avatars.=
 His realization, the one he advocated, is a static realization, an end in =
a void. This is clearly denying of the reality of this earth. I find this n=
ot in tune with what either Rama or Krshna espoused. None of them negated t=
his world. If negation of this world and life is the final aim, then why se=
nd so many avatars at crucial stages of
 evolutionary development? If the s=
piritual impact on masses is the reason for Buddha being an Avatara, then w=
hy not Jesus or Zorathrusta.? They are no less impactful in that sense. But=
 do they fit in the scheme of spiritual line that these 9 Avataras of Naray=
ana indicate in a most logical manner? No. As such many vaishnava tradition=
s in parts of India, do not consider Buddha to be an avatara. Realization, =
to be complete and holistic, must be both static and dynamic, outside of li=
fe as well as inside of life. That is why the Tantras formed their own kind=
 of spiritual philosophy, of the world as body of Shakti and therefore an o=
bject of reverence and realization. 7. The original literature of the Nath =
Yogis used to mention 9 chakras. These are centers of psychological functio=
ns. 6 inside the human body and 3 too subtle, or non-developed in most peop=
le, even seekers. It is my belief that each of the 9 Avataras - excluding B=
uddha - correspond to the full
 power and force of one of these 9 Chakras. =
Similarly, the 9 grahas, or that which can modify consciousness or allow th=
e consciousness to explore and express itself is various possiblities, are =
9 in number. The lagna is a reference point and not a graha. Therefore the =
chief Avatars who represent the parable of evolution are nine in number. An=
d the ninth of the sequence is yet to come. 8. I cannot comment on which gr=
aha would typically represent which Avatara. I know of what the BPHS says, =
however, it is my belief - feel free to disagree with it -:)[one cannot rul=
e out some deep-rooted corruption of understanding or textual misrepresenta=
tion in this Kali-Yuga] - that the Atmah among the Avataras has not yet app=
eared. It will be Kalki, or as Vimalananda seems to say in the Aghora books=
, Nishkalanka - the stainless one. There is only one thing which is perfect=
ly stainless, the Atmah .After a Nirguna/Gunatita awastha comes living in t=
he full and complete
 purity and might and force and strength of the Atmah.=
 By the sheer dint of his purity the last Avatara will burn away opposing f=
orces of this world and fulfill the purpose of evolution. Even Krshna used =
diplomacy at various points in his adult life to achieve his ends. Kalki, I=
 am speculating, won't even need that. The white horse and that sword is a =
metaphor. He will be the only one capable enough to rectify the various err=
ors and corruptions that beset our age. Well, this is how I look at the sto=
ry of Avataras. It is perfectly ok not to agree with my views, but I am rea=
sonably sanguine now that this is what is closer to truth. -Regards =C2=A0R=
